      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1999_Solutions_1999s_page_001_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "an(an−1 + an+1). Then",
        "bbox": [
          0.5568627450980392,
          0.16545454545454547,
          0.7074509803921568,
          0.1812121212121212
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1999_Solutions_1999s_page_001_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Therefore, if F (x) is the given function, we have and similarly 2b2n + b2n−1 = b2n+1, so that {bn} satis- fies the same recurrence as {an}. Since further b0 = 1, b1 = 2 (where we use the recurrence for {an } to cal- culate a−1 = 0), we deduce that bn = an for all n. In particular, a2 + a2+1 = b2n+2 = a2n+2.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12705882352941175,
          0.22181818181818183,
          0.44784313725490194,
          0.2381818181818182
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1999_Solutions_1999s_page_001_5",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
