      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1999_Solutions_1999s_page_001_7",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Second solution: Note that",
        "bbox": [
          0.5576470588235294,
          0.34606060606060607,
          0.7341176470588235,
          0.3612121212121212
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1999_Solutions_1999s_page_001_6",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "so we may set f (x) = (3x + 3)/2, g(x) = 5x/2, and h(x) = −x + 2.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12549019607843137,
          0.3472727272727273,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.3793939393939394
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1999_Solutions_1999s_page_001_8",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A−2 First solution: First factor p(x) = q(x)r(x), where q has all real roots and r has all complex roots. Notice that each root of q has even multiplicity, otherwise p would have a sign change at that root. Thus q(x) has a square root s(x).",
        "bbox": [
          0.09333333333333334,
          0.3903030303030303,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.4636363636363636
        ],
        "order": 9
      }
    ]
