    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "mineru_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1999_Solutions_1999s_page_001_13",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Second solution: We proceed by induction on the de- gree of p, with base case where p has degree 0. As in the first solution, we may reduce to a smaller degree in case p has any real roots, so assume it has none. Then p(x) > 0 for all real x, and since p(x) → ∞ for x → ±∞, p has a minimum value c. Now p(x) − c has real roots, so as above, we deduce that p(x) − c is a sum of squares. Now add one more square, namely (√c)2, to get p(x) as a sum of squares.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12627450980392158,
          0.6781818181818182,
          0.49019607843137253,
          0.8096969696969697
        ],
        "order": 16
      }
    ]
